      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Martin Luther King Jr.'s nonviolent approach was indeed the most effective strategy for the Civil Rights Movement, as it garnered widespread sympathy and support from the public and media. While there was some debate, the violent backlash from segregationists and the brutality they inflicted on peaceful protesters highlighted the necessity of nonviolence. Malcolm X and the Black Power movement advocated for more militant approaches, but they were often overshadowed by the success of King's peaceful protests. The debate about nonviolence versus militancy was less about effectiveness and more about the broader strategy for achieving racial equality. King’s approach was the most successful in the context of the time, leading to the passage of landmark legislation.",
